, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Bryn, Lancashire, England":"Bryn, Lancashire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gerard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Camille, Jean-Pierre, Murielle, Emile, Pascal, Pierre, Agathe, Alain, Aldes, Antoine, Armand.","French (<b>Gérard</b>), Walloon (mainly <b>Gérard</b>), and English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Gérard</i>, <i>Gerard</i> (from Old French <i>Gerart</i>, <i>Girart</i>), composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. As a surname of French origin it is also found in Haiti. Compare   Garrard   and also French   Guerard  , English   Garard  ,   Gerrard  , and   Jarrard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Enzo, Gaspare, Luigi, Rocco, Antonio, Canio, Carmine, Filippo, Francesco, Giovanni, Libero.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  ). This surname is also found in southern France.","German and French (mainly Nord): Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name German   Gerhard  , French <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ), using the genitive of the Latinized form <i>Gerardus</i>."]},{"name":"Garrison","meanings":["English: from a shortened form of Middle English <i>Gerardson</i>, a patronymic from the personal name   Gerard   + <i>son</i>, or an Anglicized form of its Dutch cognate   Gerritsen  . The English surname is probably in most cases of Flemish or Dutch origin. It was brought to Britain by immigrants from the Low Countries, especially in the 15th and 16th centuries.","Americanized form of Jewish   Gerson   (see   Gershon  ).","Americanized form of Dutch   Gerritsen  ."]},{"name":"Garrard","meanings":["English (London and East Anglia): variant of   Gerard  .","Altered form of French <b>Gérard</b> (see   Gerard  ).","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Geenen","meanings":["Dutch, Flemish, and North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Geen</i>, a pet form of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Gerardo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Alberto, Alfredo, Aurelio, Carlos, Jesus, Juan, Norberto, Ramon, Tomas, Ana.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Dino, Enrico, Marco, Marco Antonio.","Spanish and Italian: from the personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  )."]},{"name":"Gerald","meanings":["English (of Norman origin); French (<b>Gérald</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerald</i>, <i>Girald</i>, composed of the elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ and <i>wald</i> ‘power, authority’. It was introduced to Britain by the Normans and was fairly common, but less so than   Gerard  , with which it was early confused. In France the much more common variants of this surname are <b>Géraud</b> and   Giraud  ."]},{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["English: variant of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Geron","meanings":["French (<b>Géron</b>): from the personal name <i>Gero</i>, <i>Gerone</i>, a short form of ancient Germanic names formed with the element <i>gār, gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, as for example <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ).","Altered form of French <b>Guérin</b> (see   Guerin  ).","English (Lancashire): of Norman origin, from the personal name <i>Geron</i> of ancient Germanic origin, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Gherardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Silvio, Alessandro, Angelo, Antonio, Donato, Egidio, Ennio, Enzo, Gildo, Lucio, Luigi, Primo.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of <i>Gherardo</i>, one of themany Italian equivalents of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Garard","meanings":["English (London and Buckinghamshire): variant of   Gerard  ."]}]},{"name":"Katharine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Katherine  , associated by folk etymology with Greek <i>katharos</i> ‘pure’. This is the preferred spelling in Germany. It is also the one used in the name of the American film star  Katharine Hepburn  (  1907–2003 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Pet form of   Christopher ;  also of   Katherine   and its variants. In the medieval period it was a pet form of   Christian   and   Christiana ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Katharine Gerard was born about 1338, in Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Peter Gerard of Bryn before 21 April 1354, in Bryn, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died after 1360, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1338–Aft 1360":"umbes 1338–pärast 1360","1335–1380":"1335–1380","1360–1416":"1360–1416","1365–1434":"1365–1434","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1338":"1338","about 1360":"umbes 1360","1434":"1434","1335":"1335","1365":"1365","Aft 1360":"pärast 1360","before 21 April 1354":"enne 21. aprilli 1354","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Abt 1338":"umbes 1338","1416":"1416","Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kingsley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bryn, Lancashire, England":"Bryn, Lancashire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1338–Aft 1360":"noin 1338–1360 jälkeen","1335–1380":"1335–1380","1360–1416":"1360–1416","1365–1434":"1365–1434","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1338":"1338","about 1360":"noin 1360","1434":"1434","1335":"1335","1365":"1365","Aft 1360":"1360 jälkeen","before 21 April 1354":"ennen vuotta 21. huhtikuuta 1354","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Abt 1338":"noin 1338","1416":"1416","Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kingsley, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bryn, Lancashire, England":"Bryn, Lancashi